From: Victor <victor.krook@everdrone.com>
Subject: [PATCH] pinctrl: sunxi: suniv-f1c100s: disable strict pinmux mode

All other sunxi pinctrl drivers (sun4i-a10, sun8i-a33, sun50i-a64, etc.)
set .disable_strict_mode = true, which allows the standard "pinctrl state
applies default config, then the consumer driver requests the GPIO"
pattern used by gpio-keys, gpio-leds, and friends.

Without it, suniv's pinmux core rejects the GPIO claim because the pin
was just claimed by the pinctrl state's mux function ("gpio_in"),
producing errors like:

    suniv-f1c100s-pinctrl 1c20800.pinctrl: pin PD9 already requested
        by gpio-keys; cannot claim for 1c20800.pinctrl:105
    gpio-keys: probe with driver gpio-keys failed with error -22

Align suniv with the rest of the sunxi family.

Signed-off-by: Victor <victor.krook@everdrone.com>
---
 drivers/pinctrl/sunxi/pinctrl-suniv-f1c100s.c | 1 +
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+)

diff --git a/drivers/pinctrl/sunxi/pinctrl-suniv-f1c100s.c b/drivers/pinctrl/sunxi/pinctrl-suniv-f1c100s.c
--- a/drivers/pinctrl/sunxi/pinctrl-suniv-f1c100s.c
+++ b/drivers/pinctrl/sunxi/pinctrl-suniv-f1c100s.c
@@ -391,6 +391,7 @@ static const struct sunxi_pinctrl_desc suniv_f1c100s_pinctrl_data = {
 	.pins = suniv_f1c100s_pins,
 	.npins = ARRAY_SIZE(suniv_f1c100s_pins),
 	.irq_banks = 3,
+	.disable_strict_mode = true,
 };

 static int suniv_pinctrl_probe(struct platform_device *pdev)
